04796nam a22006975i 9780813541129DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20052005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135411297 a10.36019/97808135411292doi  a(DE-B1597)529498  a(OCoLC)77208272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aLA227.4b.Z46 2005eb 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a378.732221 aZemsky, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRemaking the American University :bMarket-Smart and Mission-Centered /cGregory R Wegner, William F. Massy, Robert Zemsky. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction The Diminishing of Public Purpose -- t2. The Lattice and the Ratchet -- t3. The Admissions Arms Race -- t4. On Being Mission-Centered and Market-Smart -- t5. To Publish and Perish -- t6. A Value Proposition -- t7. Thwarted Innovation -- t8. Who Owns Teaching? -- t9. Making Educational Quality Job One -- t10. Not Good Enough -- t11. Crafting a Public Agenda -- t12. Dancing with Change -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt one time, universities educated new generations and were a source of social change. Today colleges and universities are less places of public purpose, than agencies of personal advantage. Remaking the American University provides a penetrating analysis of the ways market forces have shaped and distorted the behaviors, purposes, and ultimately the missions of universities and colleges over the past half-century. The authors describe how a competitive preoccupation with rankings and markets published by the media spawned an admissions arms race that drains institutional resources and energies. Equally revealing are the depictions of the ways faculty distance themselves from their universities with the resulting increase in the number of administrators, which contributes substantially to institutional costs. Other chapters focus on the impact of intercollegiate athletics on educational mission, even among selective institutions; on the unforeseen result of higher education's "outsourcing" a substantial share of the scholarly publication function to for-profit interests; and on the potentially dire consequences of today's zealous investments in e-learning. A central question extends through this series of explorations: Can universities and colleges today still choose to be places of public purpose? In the answers they provide, both sobering and enlightening, the authors underscore a consistent and powerful lesson-academic institutions cannot ignore the workings of the markets. The challenge ahead is to learn how to better use those markets to achieve public purposes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aMassy, William F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWegner, Gregory R, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354112940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541129423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813541129/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aE